{"questionId":"9083154","questionHtml":"<p>A satellite orbits planet <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>X</mtext></math> with a speed <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mtext>X</mtext></msub></math>&nbsp;at a distance <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>r</mtext></math>&nbsp;from the centre of planet <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>X</mtext></math>. Another&nbsp;satellite orbits planet <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math> at a speed of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mtext>y</mtext></msub></math> at a distance <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>r</mtext></math>&nbsp;from the centre of planet <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math>. The mass&nbsp;of planet <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>X</mtext></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>M</mi></math> and the mass of planet <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>M</mi></math>. What is the ratio of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mtext>X</mtext></msub><msub><mi>v</mi><mtext>y</mtext></msub></mfrac></math>?<br><br>A.&nbsp; 0.25</p>\n<p>B.&nbsp; 0.5</p>\n<p>C.&nbsp; 2.0</p>\n<p>D.&nbsp; 4.0</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>B</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9083154","referenceCode":"21M.1A.HL.TZ2.32","subjectId":"59-dp-physics-first-assessment-2025","title":"A satellite orbits planet X with a speed vX at a distance r from the centre of planet X. Another satellite orbits planet Y at a speed of vy at a distance r from the centre of plane","paper":"1A","level":"HL","questionNumber":"32","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["D. Fields","D.1 Gravitational fields"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}